The most famous and widely recognized GitHub repository for web-attack payloads and cheat sheets is [swisskyrepo/PayloadsAllTheThings](https://github.com/swisskyrepo/payloadsallthethings). It serves as a central hub for penetration testers and security researchers globally. [1, 2] 
Beyond that singular repo, several other legendary open-source repositories and frameworks host major attack techniques, payloads, and wordlists.
## 1. Web Vulnerability & Payload Repositories

* PayloadsAllTheThings: The gold standard for web application security. It features structured bypasses and payloads for SQL Injection, Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), Command Injection, and directory traversal. [1, 3] 
* [danielmiessler/SecLists](https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists): The absolute go-to companion for security testers. It contains comprehensive collections of usernames, passwords, URLs, sensitive data patterns, and fuzzing payloads for brute-force attacks. [4, 5] 
* [payload-box repositories](https://github.com/payload-box): A highly structured collection of dedicated repositories tracking specific vectors, such as the [Open Redirect Payload List](https://github.com/payload-box/open-redirect-payload-list), XSS, and SQLi lists. [6] 

## 2. Post-Exploitation & Command Shell Repositories

* swisskyrepo/ReverseShellCheatsheet: A legendary collection of one-liners to spin up interactive reverse shells across dozens of languages (Python, Bash, PowerShell, PHP, etc.).
* [samratashok/nishang](https://github.com/samratashok/nishang): A widely recognized framework of PowerShell scripts and payloads used specifically for offensive security, post-exploitation, and execution on Windows environments.

## 3. Exploitation Frameworks & Tool Repositories

* [rapid7/metasploit-framework](https://github.com/rapid7/metasploit-framework): The official open-source repository for the most famous exploitation software in the world. It includes thousands of built-in exploits, auxiliary scanners, and modular payloads (like Meterpreter). [7] 
* gentilkiwi/mimikatz: The iconic post-exploitation tool repository used to extract plain-text passwords, hash dumps, and Kerberos tickets directly from Windows memory.
* hak5/usbrubberducky-payloads: The official hub for DuckyScript community payloads. It is used for Keystroke Injection attacks using hotplug hardware tools. [8] 

## 4. Curated "Awesome" Attack Directories [4] 

* [The-Art-of-Hacking/h4cker](https://github.com/The-Art-of-Hacking/h4cker): Maintained by cybersecurity expert Omar Santos, this massive repo hosts thousands of links regarding exploit development, offensive AI, and ethical hacking resources. [5, 9] 
* [enaqx/awesome-pentest](https://github.com/enaqx/awesome-pentest): A collection of hundreds of open-source penetration testing tools, covering network attacks, social engineering, and execution environments. [10] 

